                    <p>In this particular case, the evidence against the Defendant supported a conviction. We attempted to achieve a straight plea to Speed. We were shot down but did not give up. On the court date, after discussions with the Prosecution, an agreement was reached for a plea of guilty to the Speeding charge. The same resolution request, that had been rejected, by the Crown, for months. To the extreme delight of our client the Stunt Driving Charge would be withdrawn. However, it was discovered that the police officer was away on course, and would not be attending the court proceedings. The astute Paralegal would not consent to an adjournment, even though the Crown had offered to withdrawn the Stunt and, as a direct result, of 37 years of legal experience, tenacity and legal know how both the charges of Speeding and Stunt Driving were withdrawn. Our client walked out of court with no conviction, no demerit points or insurance implications.</p>
                    <h4 class="first">What Is Stunt Driving In Ontario?</h4>
                    <p>Stunt driving does not simply include driving at dangerous speeds or performing bold jumps and skids with your vehicle. There are actually a surprising number of driving activities that can lead to this type of traffic ticket, including:</p>
                    <ul>
                    <li>Driving 50 or more KM per HR over the speed limit</li>
                    <li>Driving your car in a way that interferes with the flow of traffic, including preventing cars from passing without reason</li>
                    <li>Performing “donuts” – spinning your vehicle in a circular motion</li>
                    <li>Having passengers in your trunk</li>
                    <li>Unsafe turns</li>
                    <li>Driving with the intent of losing some or all traction</li>
                    </ul>
                    <p>These are just a few of the activities that can lead to a stunt driving ticket. Many other actions that put yourself and other drivers at risk can also lead to dangerous driving or stunt driving tickets.</p>
                    <h4 class="first">Punishments for Ontario Stunt Driving</h4>
                    <p>If you are found to be stunt driving in Toronto or throughout Ontario, you could face the following punishments and costs:</p>
                    <ul>
                    <li>A fine of $2,000 to $10,000</li>
                    <li>A jail sentence of up to six months</li>
                    <li>Suspension of your driver’s license for seven days</li>
                    <li>Your vehicle may be impounded for seven days</li>
                    </ul>
                    <p>Previous or concurrent tickets may increase the severity of your punishment. Another substantial cost of a stunt driving ticket is that your insurance costs will increase and some insurance companies may not want to provide coverage for you at all.</p>
